%3EMichelle%20Lee%20Photography%2FGetty%20Images%3B%20bhofack2%2FGetty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EBecause%20of%20its%20preservative%20qualities%2C%20salt%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F1977%2F06%2F16%2Farchives%2Fsalt-it-away-shake-it-with-style.html%5C%22%3Ewas%20worth%20its%20weight%20in%20gold%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20ancient%20Greece.%20Before%20that%2C%20it%20was%20used%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fseasalt.com%2Fsalt-101%2Fabout-salt%2Fhistory-of-salt%5C%22%3Eofferings%3C%2Fa%3E%20made%20to%20Egyptian%20gods.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnd%20Rome%20even%20named%20a%20street%20after%20it%3A%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fimperiumromanum.pl%2Fen%2Fcuriosities%2Fvia-salaria-roman-road%2F%23google_vignette%5C%22%3EThe%20Via%20Salaria%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0connected%20the%20capital%20to%20the%20Adriatic%20Sea.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERoman%20soldiers%20were%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.npr.org%2Fsections%2F13.7%2F2014%2F11%2F08%2F362478685%2Ffrom-salt-to-salary-linguists-take-a-page-from-science%23%3A~%3Atext%3DBeing%2520so%2520valuable%252C%2520soldiers%2520in%2Cas%2520the%2520word%2520%2522salary.%2522%5C%22%3Epaid%3C%2Fa%3E%20a%20monthly%20wage%20called%20%26quot%3Bsalarium%2C%26quot%3B%20which%20was%20later%20adapted%20into%20the%20English%20language%20as%20the%20word%20%26quot%3Bsalary.%26quot%3B%20Even%20the%20phrase%20%26quot%3Bnot%20worth%20his%20salt%26quot%3B%20comes%20from%20trading%20salt%20for%20slaves%20in%20Greece.%20And%20soon%2C%20having%20salt%20became%20emblematic%20of%20a%20person's%20social%20status.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3E2.%20Body%20modifications%20were%20all%20the%20rage%20in%20Asia.%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%22355%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Young%20Tonkin%20with%20teeth%20painted%20black%2C%20c.%201905.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64e8456b52bc2d001991d141%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22596%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EYoung%20Tonkin%20with%20teeth%20painted%20black%2C%201905.%3Cp%3ECommon%20source%2F%20wikimedia%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20ancient%20Japanese%20tradition%20of%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Flivejapan.com%2Fen%2Farticle-a0001026%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EOhaguro%2C%20or%20blackening%20one's%20teeth%3C%2Fa%3E%20by%20lacquering%20them%2C%20was%20once%20a%20status%20symbol.%20Traces%20of%20this%20practice%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftankenjapan.com%2Fohaguro-why-japanese-women-once-dyed-their-teeth-black-and-where-its-still-seen-today%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edate%20back%20to%20the%2012th%20century%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20why%3F%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESimply%20because%20black-colored%20objects%20were%20considered%20to%20be%20beautiful%20%E2%80%94%20making%20them%20revered%20and%20sought%20after.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20centuries%2C%20weird%20body%20modification%20trends%20symbolized%20wealth%20and%20good%20breeding.%20Take%2C%20for%20example%2C%20Chinese%20women%20binding%20their%20feet%20to%20turn%20them%20into%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.npr.org%2F2007%2F03%2F19%2F8966942%2Fpainful-memories-for-chinas-footbinding-survivors%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%26quot%3Bthree-inch%20golden%20lotuses.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat%20practice%20was%20seemingly%20inspired%20by%20a%20tenth-century%20court%20dancer%20and%20eventually%20became%20a%20tool%20for%20social%20mobility%20for%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thoughtco.com%2Fthe-history-of-foot-binding-in-china-195228%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eupper%20classes%20of%20Han%20Chinese%20society%3C%2Fa%3E.%20It%20was%20eventually%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Fscience%2Ffootbinding%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eoutlawed%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEven%20now%2C%20women%20have%20been%20conditioned%20to%20believe%20that%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fsipofculture.com%2F2022%2F02%2F09%2Fhow-we-are-programmed-to-believe-that-beauty-is-pain%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ebeauty%20is%20pain%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20forcing%20them%20to%20pluck%20or%20shave%20their%20hair%2C%20squeeze%20their%20feet%20into%20high%20heels%2C%20or%20surgically%20enhance%20their%20anatomy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3E3.%20Pineapples%20were%20once%20considered%20to%20be%20the%20epitome%20of%20luxury.%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221881%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22pineapple%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F60b00fa102ac410018f9347a%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221410%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EPineapple%20is%20not%20only%20a%20delicious%20snack%2C%20but%20a%20healthy%20one%2C%20too.%3Cp%3EHuyen%20Nguyen%20%2F%20EyeEm%2FGetty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ESome%20250%20years%20ago%2C%20pineapples%20were%20the%20epitome%20of%20wealth%20and%20good%20breeding.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%201770s%2C%20these%20unlikely%20status%20symbols%20entered%20the%20zeitgeist%20to%20mean%20anything%20of%20top%20quality.%20There%20was%20no%20higher%20compliment%20than%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.com%2Fnews%2Fuk-england-53432877%5C%22%3E%26quot%3Ba%20pineapple%20of%20the%20finest%20flavor.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFrancesca%20Beauman%2C%20the%20author%20of%20%26quot%3BThe%20Pineapple%3A%20King%20of%20Fruits%2C%26quot%3B%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fedition.cnn.com%2Fstyle%2Fpineapples-luxury-symbol-britain%2Findex.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Etold%20CNN%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0that%20pineapples%20were%20sought%20after%20because%20the%20travelers%20who%20experienced%20eating%20them%20in%20the%20New%20World%20raved%20about%20their%20flavor.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThese%20fruits%20were%20so%20luxurious%20that%20they%20were%20fit%20for%20royalty.%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.rct.uk%2Fcollection%2F406896%2Fcharles-ii-presented-with-a-pineapple%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EAn%20oil%20painting%20titled%20%26quot%3BCharles%20II%20Presented%20with%20a%20Pineapple%26quot%3B%3C%2Fa%3E%20featured%20the%20English%20monarch%20perched%20on%20a%20terrace.%20A%20man%20%E2%80%94%20presumed%20to%20be%20John%20Rose%2C%20the%20royal%20gardener%20%E2%80%94%20kneels%20before%20him.%20He%20appears%20to%20be%20offering%20the%20royal%20a%20pineapple%2C%20then%20considered%20a%20rare%20and%20highly%20valued%20exotic%20fruit.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20is%20even%20a%20record%20of%20Charles%20II%20getting%20the%20first%20taste%20of%20the%20fruit.%20We%20don't%20know%20what%20the%20monarch%20thought%20of%20it%2C%20but%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.rct.uk%2Fcollection%2Fthemes%2Ftrails%2Fpublic-dining-in-the-reign-of-charles-ii-1630-1685%2Fcharles-ii-presented%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eaccording%20to%20the%20Royal%20Collection%20Trust%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20the%20record%20keeper%20was%20disappointed%20by%20the%20taste.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3E4.%20Mummy-unwrapping%20parties%20were%20all%20the%20rage%20in%20the%2018th%20and%2019th%20century.%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20mummy%20is%20shown%20inside%20its%20large%20wodden%20sarcophagus.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F63cf9f3d0a375c0018fa8af0%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222751%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20mummy%20inside%20its%20sarcophagus.%3Cp%3ESahar%20Saleem%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EAs%20a%20fascination%20with%20Egypt%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ripleys.com%2Fweird-news%2Fmummy-unwrapping-parties-of-the-victorian-era%2F%5C%22%3Etook%20a%20hold%20over%3C%2Fa%3E%20Victorian-era%20England%2C%20mummy-unwrapping%20parties%20entered%20the%20scene.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHeld%20in%20the%20private%20homes%20of%20the%20societal%20elite%2C%20these%20events%20married%20the%20lot's%20fascination%20with%20science%20%E2%80%94%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.mirror.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fweird-news%2Fgruesome-mummy-unwrapping-parties-victorians-25491601%5C%22%3Eand%20morbidity%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETypically%20these%20parties%20would%20involve%20mummies%20brought%20in%20from%20Egypt%20and%20slowly%20unwrapped%20in%20front%20of%20curious%20onlookers.%20And%20no%20unwrapping%20party%20was%20as%20popular%20as%20Thomas%20Pettigrew's%2C%20a%C2%A0surgeon%C2%A0and%C2%A0antiquarian.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThere's%20even%20a%20record%20of%20one.%20On%20a%20cold%20January%20evening%20in%201834%2C%20a%20few%20lucky%20Londoners%20got%20the%20opportunity%20to%20witness%20the%20unwrapping%20of%20an%20Egyptian%20mummy%20of%20the%2021st%20dynasty%20at%20the%20Royal%20College%20of%20Surgeons.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPettigrew%20soon%20became%20the%20pioneer%20of%20such%20events%2C%20holding%20elaborate%20unwrappings%20in%20front%20of%20shocked%20audiences.%20He%20was%20even%20approached%20to%20mummify%20the%20Duke%20of%20Hamilton%20at%20the%20time%2C%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.atlasobscura.com%2Farticles%2Fvictorian-party-people-unrolled-mummies-for-fun%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ea%20fan%20of%20his%20work%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20not%20everyone%20was%20a%20fan%3A%20Egyptologist%20John%20J.%20Johnston%20felt%20these%20parties%20were%20%26quot%3Bdisgusting.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BBodies%20are%20supposed%20to%20be%20treated%20with%20respect%20%E2%80%94%20you%20can't%20deal%20with%20people%20in%20that%20way%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pastfactory.com%2Fculture%2Fweird-status-symbols-throughout-history%2F20%2F%5C%22%3Esaid%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3E5.%20Crumbling%20structures%20were%20the%20hottest%2